I'm in the same boat with you on the generalized imposter syndrome, but it helps me that I don't drop anything here before the first draft of the entire piece. If I went episodic like many of the other writefags I would have quit before my second story.
I'd suggest two things. Outline a little, and write something each day. Even if it's only a warmup exercise, every day is a chance to make progress. If you wait for inspiration, you're losing 90% or more of your chances for progress. Doesn't have to be good. You'll learn how many nifty ideas are really falling in your lap.

I could mention my word count goal for the year. Out of 90 some days, I wrote something on almost all of them. And I've already kept more first draft material than some will write all year. Tossed a lot out as well. I'm not getting paid either (soon, though), but the grind I've done since November has sharpened my skills. Look anytime the drawfags start talking about fundamental exercises and sketch work. Same thing.

And guess what? I have two decent sized stories I'm sitting on, waffling if I'm good. You don't get over the anxiety. You just get better at kicking it in the teeth.

>without constantly confusing or naming them directly
If you're not naming them in the dialogue, then tagging them in the dialogue or giving them an action or other movement makes it clear who is speaking.
This is no different than first person, but requires a bit more care. I love the technique of free indirect speech, and abuse it in my first drafts. If I didn't clean that up the result would be a head hopping omniscient narrator.
I could go more in depth later how I currently build up non-exposition paragraphs as well.

My scifi recommendation is anything by iain banks. Stross as well, but he dabbles in first person too
